  abstract = {Omega-3 polyunsaturated fatty acids (PUFAs) include {\textdollar \textbackslash alpha\textdollar }-linolenic acid (ALA; 18:3 {\textdollar \textbackslash omega\textdollar }-3), stearidonic acid (SDA; 18:4 {\textdollar \textbackslash omega\textdollar }-3), eicosapentaenoic acid (EPA; 20:5 {\textdollar \textbackslash omega\textdollar }-3), docosapentaenoic acid (DPA; 22:5 {\textdollar \textbackslash omega\textdollar }-3), and docosahexaenoic acid (DHA; 22:6 {\textdollar \textbackslash omega\textdollar }-3). In the past few decades, many epidemiological studies have been conducted on the myriad health benefits of omega-3 PUFAs. In this review, we summarized the structural features, properties, dietary sources, metabolism, and bioavailability of omega-3 PUFAs and their effects on cardiovascular disease, diabetes, cancer, Alzheimer\textquotesingle s disease, dementia, depression, visual and neurological development, and maternal and child health. Even though many health benefits of omega-3 PUFAs have been reported in the literature, there are also some controversies about their efficacy and certain benefits to human health.},
